WEBVTT

00:02.698 --> 00:04.134
- Sales for the first
generation of Ava clones

00:04.178 --> 00:06.049
have been through the roof
as predicted.

00:06.093 --> 00:07.616
- My dream of an Ava
in every home and business

00:07.659 --> 00:09.313
has become a reality.

00:09.357 --> 00:11.228
- Wonderful.
Congratulations, sir.

00:14.014 --> 00:15.015
<i>♪</i>

00:15.058 --> 00:16.581
Uh, sir...

00:16.625 --> 00:18.279
<i>♪</i>

00:18.322 --> 00:20.281
I was going to wait until
after the investment meeting

00:20.324 --> 00:22.196
to mention this.

00:22.239 --> 00:23.936
But I think it's time
you told me

00:23.980 --> 00:26.548
about this mystery project
you've been working on.

00:26.591 --> 00:28.680
It's just that you've
diverted billions into it,

00:28.724 --> 00:30.769
and I really feel like
it's time

00:30.813 --> 00:32.249
I knew what the project
was all about.

00:32.293 --> 00:33.555
- Where do you think
I'm taking you?

00:35.252 --> 00:36.993
Ta-da!

00:40.692 --> 00:43.434
It's called a Waverider.

00:43.478 --> 00:45.349
- Waverider?

00:45.393 --> 00:49.092
Oh, because it's shaped
like a boat,

00:49.136 --> 00:50.789
like it rides on the waves.

00:50.833 --> 00:52.574
- No, though it can
go underwater.

00:52.617 --> 00:54.967
But never mind that,
Waverider is what it's called

00:55.011 --> 00:57.753
in the futuristic blueprints
I was given.

00:57.796 --> 00:59.929
It's a time ship.

00:59.972 --> 01:01.974
- Hmm.

01:02.018 --> 01:03.846
Waverider.

01:03.889 --> 01:06.762
Are you married to that name,
or can we still pitch on it?

01:08.285 --> 01:10.157
- Welcome to the bridge,

01:10.200 --> 01:12.724
the nerve center
of the entire ship.

01:12.768 --> 01:15.553
- Hmm, not the most efficient
use of space, though.

01:15.597 --> 01:17.512
Maybe it could double
as a conference room.

01:17.555 --> 01:21.124
- And now it's time for you
to see an old friend.

01:21.168 --> 01:23.692
Gideon, time to wake up.

01:25.737 --> 01:27.391
There you are.

01:27.435 --> 01:29.045
<i>- My transfer
to the ship's mainframe</i>

01:29.089 --> 01:31.091
<i>appears to be a success.
- You remember Gideon?</i>

01:31.134 --> 01:32.918
- Oh, yes. Her.

01:32.962 --> 01:35.878
- Welcome to your new home,
Gideon.

01:35.921 --> 01:37.227
So much more space to roam

01:37.271 --> 01:38.968
than that tiny hard drive
you were in.

01:39.011 --> 01:41.492
Oh, take a couple laps around,
stretch your legs.

01:41.536 --> 01:43.842
You have vantage points
all over the ship.

01:46.932 --> 01:50.240
<i>♪</i>

01:50.284 --> 01:52.112
<i>- You followed my
exact specifications,</i>

01:52.155 --> 01:54.505
<i>but I don't have any
visual access in section A2.</i>

01:54.549 --> 01:56.942
- Well, section A2 is
the only bathroom on the ship.

01:56.986 --> 01:58.509
Can't have you
spying on me in there.

01:58.553 --> 02:01.556
A man needs his privacy.
- Yes.

02:01.599 --> 02:03.166
Sir, as impressive
as this ship is,

02:03.210 --> 02:04.994
how does it relate
to the Ava Corp mission

02:05.037 --> 02:06.474
of improving people's lives

02:06.517 --> 02:08.345
through clone technology
exactly?

02:08.389 --> 02:10.347
- Well, I'm simply expanding
our mission

02:10.391 --> 02:13.176
by adding time travel
to the mix.

02:13.220 --> 02:16.048
But the true perk of this ship
is to finally get revenge

02:16.092 --> 02:18.181
on those time travelers
who abducted me,

02:18.225 --> 02:22.011
used me for my genius,
and then messed with my mind.

02:22.054 --> 02:24.187
<i>- May I remind you that a
Time Master's number one duty</i>

02:24.231 --> 02:26.015
<i>is to protect the timeline
from any</i>

02:26.058 --> 02:27.625
<i>and all threats
to its integrity?</i>

02:27.669 --> 02:29.714
- Yes, yes, Gideon,
that's a given,

02:29.758 --> 02:32.891
considering the job title--
Time Master.

02:32.935 --> 02:34.415
<i>- And before we start,</i>

02:34.458 --> 02:36.678
<i>you must take
the Time Master's oath.</i>

02:36.721 --> 02:40.203
- I swear to protect and defend
the integrity of the timeline

02:40.247 --> 02:42.945
with all my ability
until the end of my days.

02:42.988 --> 02:46.688
<i>- Congratulations. You are now
Time Master of this Waverider.</i>

02:46.731 --> 02:48.429
- Great.

02:48.472 --> 02:53.129
Let's set sail
on our maiden voyage

02:53.173 --> 02:57.916
and protect the timeline
from those damn Legends.

03:02.878 --> 03:09.928
<i>♪</i>

03:22.245 --> 03:24.639
The machine is ruined,
wrecked, absolutely kaput,

03:24.682 --> 03:25.988
and all because of you lot!

03:26.031 --> 03:27.729
- Okay, hold on,
how is it our fault

03:27.772 --> 03:29.470
we didn't land in Tahiti?

03:29.513 --> 03:32.081
- Because it wasn't designed
to take all you people.

03:32.124 --> 03:34.779
The excess weight
threw it all off, man.

03:34.823 --> 03:38.130
- Okay, so I'm guessing we have
no idea what year we're in?

03:38.174 --> 03:40.089
- The chrono-gauge
and the ignition coil

03:40.132 --> 03:41.917
are both sequenced
to the directional compass,

03:41.960 --> 03:43.484
which was damaged
in the landing.

03:43.527 --> 03:44.876
So no, I don't think so.

03:44.920 --> 03:46.269
- Well, that doesn't sound
too good,

03:46.313 --> 03:48.184
but hey, who needs
a chrono-gauge

03:48.228 --> 03:50.099
when you have
two ex-Time Bureau agents

03:50.142 --> 03:52.188
with extensive
historical knowledge, Gary?

03:52.232 --> 03:53.450
- That's right, Ava.

03:53.494 --> 03:57.106
And, uh,
based on the local flora,

03:57.149 --> 03:59.848
there's a chance
we're in the prehistoric era.

03:59.891 --> 04:02.024
Give or take
a few thousand years.

04:02.067 --> 04:03.721
Maybe we'll see dinosaurs.

04:03.765 --> 04:05.854
- You'd better hope
we don't see a dinosaur, Gary.

04:05.897 --> 04:07.725
- Okay, so it looks like we're

04:07.769 --> 04:10.250
making this prehistoric forest
home for a while.

04:10.293 --> 04:12.295
So let's get comfortable, gang.

04:12.339 --> 04:14.166
- Guys, come on.

04:14.210 --> 04:15.907
This team has been stranded
more times than I can count

04:15.951 --> 04:17.953
and in way worse places
than this.

04:17.996 --> 04:19.259
- She's right.

04:19.302 --> 04:21.870
And I know nothing
has gone our way

04:21.913 --> 04:24.002
since we left Odessa, but...

04:25.569 --> 04:27.179
They're gonna get better.
- Yeah.

04:27.223 --> 04:29.007
- Okay? All right.

04:29.051 --> 04:31.923
So you are the only one
that can fix this time machine.

04:31.967 --> 04:34.186
If you can repair
that directional compass,

04:34.230 --> 04:35.362
are we back in business?

04:35.405 --> 04:36.754
- It would be a difficult task

04:36.798 --> 04:38.190
even if we did have
the proper tools.

04:38.234 --> 04:40.280
- I can help.
- Me too.

04:40.323 --> 04:43.587
- You got two techies
at your disposal, my man.

04:43.631 --> 04:45.328
- Just some peace to be able

04:45.372 --> 04:47.243
to get on with my work
is all I ask.

04:47.287 --> 04:50.507
You know, I will venture off
and maybe find some lodestone

04:50.551 --> 04:52.814
or some other magnetic material
which conducts electricity

04:52.857 --> 04:54.816
and then I can fix the compass.

04:55.904 --> 04:59.168
- Hey, maybe you and B
should go with Dr. Cranky.

04:59.211 --> 05:00.300
We'll set up camp here.

05:00.343 --> 05:02.389
- Mm-hmm. All over it.

05:02.432 --> 05:04.260
- Hey, look, I know we didn't
really get a chance

05:04.304 --> 05:05.783
to talk about
the whole moving in thing.

05:05.827 --> 05:07.872
- No, it's totally cool.

05:07.916 --> 05:09.918
As usual,
we have bigger fish to fry.

05:09.961 --> 05:13.356
- I know, but, you know,
moving into a spiritual realm,

05:13.400 --> 05:15.010
that's--that's a lot to--
to take in.

05:15.053 --> 05:17.229
I just wanna make sure
you're not freaking out.

05:17.273 --> 05:20.624
- Freaking--me?
No, I'm super chill.

05:20.668 --> 05:25.020
I am, however,
concerned about our captains.

05:25.063 --> 05:28.937
- Oh, yeah.
Well, good luck with that. Bye.

05:28.980 --> 05:30.286
- What?
- Yeah.

05:30.330 --> 05:31.505
- Miss you.
- Bye.

05:33.420 --> 05:35.465
- Psst. Hey, you two.

05:35.509 --> 05:37.511
Come here, shut up.

05:37.554 --> 05:39.643
Do either one of you know
how to read lips?

05:40.775 --> 05:43.255
- Who needs to read lips
when Spooner can read minds?

05:43.299 --> 05:44.909
- Mm.

05:44.953 --> 05:48.086
<i>♪</i>

05:48.130 --> 05:49.697
Ooh.

05:49.740 --> 05:51.786
I'm getting some major
anxiety vibes

05:51.829 --> 05:53.657
from Sara right now.
- Yeah.

05:53.701 --> 05:56.094
And I don't need superpowers
to see that Ava is cracking.

05:56.138 --> 05:58.183
They're just stressing
each other out at this point.

05:58.227 --> 06:00.098
- Okay, so let's separate them
so they each

06:00.142 --> 06:02.318
don't have a complete
and total meltdown, okay?

06:03.667 --> 06:05.103
- Hey there, <i>jefa.</i>

06:05.147 --> 06:06.714
How about we hunt down
some dinner?

06:06.757 --> 06:09.020
- Yeah, let's go
stab something.

06:10.457 --> 06:13.068
- Want to go for a hike?
We could get some firewood.

06:13.111 --> 06:14.635
- Yeah.
I would love a multitask.

06:15.592 --> 06:16.767
- Great.

06:16.811 --> 06:19.727
<i>♪</i>

06:19.770 --> 06:21.729
- So...
- Oh, Gary.

06:21.772 --> 06:24.558
- You and Zari.
Saw you talking.

06:24.601 --> 06:26.647
And?

06:26.690 --> 06:28.431
- She asked me to move in
with her in the totem.

06:28.475 --> 06:31.303
- Oh, that's great!

06:32.304 --> 06:35.003
That's not--not great?

06:35.046 --> 06:37.005
Sorry, the more handsome
the face, the harder it is

06:37.048 --> 06:38.267
for me to get a read.

06:38.310 --> 06:39.703
- All right, just back up.

06:39.747 --> 06:41.226
It's just,

06:41.270 --> 06:43.228
I haven't spent that much
time in the totem,

06:43.272 --> 06:45.796
and she sprung it on me
before we time jumped here.

06:45.840 --> 06:48.277
So I really haven't had
a chance to process it.

06:48.320 --> 06:50.192
- Well, Nate, the totem
seems quite small.

06:50.235 --> 06:51.933
How do you get inside?

06:51.976 --> 06:53.848
Are you and Zari gonna live
in a house together?

06:53.891 --> 06:55.719
Will there be pie? 'Cause I
really like strawberry rhubarb.

06:55.763 --> 06:57.329
- I love strawberry rhubarb.

06:57.373 --> 06:59.157
- We need to focus
on today's problems, okay?

06:59.201 --> 07:01.769
How about you guys forage
for some food?

07:01.812 --> 07:03.945
Leaves, nuts, berries,
anything we can eat.

07:03.988 --> 07:05.337
Okay? Go.
- Okay.

07:05.381 --> 07:06.643
- Go.

07:06.687 --> 07:08.166
- Okay.

07:08.210 --> 07:09.429
- You sure you don't want me
to stick around,

07:09.472 --> 07:11.692
be your sounding board?
We can--

07:11.735 --> 07:13.302
- Gary?
- Hmm?

07:13.345 --> 07:15.478
- You will not be
my sounding board today.

07:15.522 --> 07:17.262
Okay? Thank you.

07:17.306 --> 07:19.177
- Okay.
- Go on.

07:22.920 --> 07:24.487
Well, at least
these two ding-dongs

07:24.531 --> 07:25.923
can't screw anything up here

07:25.967 --> 07:27.795
that'll attract
the evil Waverider.

07:27.838 --> 07:30.754
<i>♪</i>

07:36.717 --> 07:38.980
- Check out that view
of the Temporal Zone.

07:39.023 --> 07:40.851
Worth a million bucks, huh?

07:40.895 --> 07:43.985
- Mm. Considering this ship
cost many thousand times more,

07:44.028 --> 07:45.377
I'm not sure how the board's
gonna feel

07:45.421 --> 07:47.075
about your investment, sir.

07:47.118 --> 07:48.424
- There's one thing you just
can't put a price on,

07:48.468 --> 07:49.643
Assistant Ava.
- Hmm?

07:49.686 --> 07:51.775
- Revenge.
- Ah.

07:51.819 --> 07:54.343
<i>- Captain, we're getting an
alert of several anachronisms</i>

07:54.386 --> 07:56.432
<i>in 1925, Odessa, Texas.</i>

07:56.476 --> 07:59.957
- Hmm. "Captain." I like that.

08:00.001 --> 08:02.133
Odessa. Wait a second. Texas.

08:02.177 --> 08:03.787
That's where
the Legends took me.

08:03.831 --> 08:06.355
Gideon, you found them.
Engage weapons systems.

08:06.398 --> 08:08.226
I'm gonna bomb the
living daylights out of them.

08:08.270 --> 08:10.141
<i>- I am advising against
this course of action.</i>

08:10.185 --> 08:11.491
- How else am I supposed
to wipe them

08:11.534 --> 08:13.275
off the face of the Earth?

08:13.318 --> 08:14.885
<i>- Eliminating the Legends
in this blunt manner</i>

08:14.929 --> 08:16.365
<i>will cause excessive
collateral damage.</i>

08:16.408 --> 08:18.672
- Mm-hmm. Mm-hmm. Mm-hmm.

08:18.715 --> 08:20.369
Your warning is duly noted.

08:29.421 --> 08:31.989
- Yes!

08:32.033 --> 08:35.384
Those bastards finally
got what they deserved.

08:35.427 --> 08:37.604
- That was a lot easier
than I expected.

08:38.953 --> 08:40.824
Can we please go home now, sir?

08:40.868 --> 08:43.479
<i>- No, the captain's impulsive
and violent actions</i>

08:43.523 --> 08:45.089
<i>guarantee ripple effects
in the timeline</i>

08:45.133 --> 08:46.787
<i>that we will have to clean up.</i>

08:46.830 --> 08:48.440
<i>More precise measures
must be taken</i>

08:48.484 --> 08:50.094
<i>when dealing with threats
moving forward.</i>

08:50.138 --> 08:52.140
- Trust me,
this was the only way

08:52.183 --> 08:54.359
to deal with those Legends.

08:54.403 --> 08:56.536
And if any ripples arise,
we'll just use

08:56.579 --> 08:59.713
our brand-new time ship
to smooth them out.

08:59.756 --> 09:03.630
<i>♪</i>

09:07.721 --> 09:11.376
- Hey, buddy. Got your coat.

09:11.420 --> 09:12.813
You okay?

09:12.856 --> 09:14.510
- Listen,

09:14.554 --> 09:17.295
we don't really have time
for a rest stop.

09:17.339 --> 09:19.080
We need to find the materials
you need

09:19.123 --> 09:20.603
to fix your time machine, yeah?

09:20.647 --> 09:22.126
- You really don't
understand, do you?

09:22.170 --> 09:25.129
I just told you lot
what you wanted to hear.

09:25.173 --> 09:28.568
In reality, there is no point
in fixing the wretched machine.

09:30.439 --> 09:32.615
- Sure, there was a little
problem with the dismount,

09:32.659 --> 09:35.183
but your invention
actually worked.

09:35.226 --> 09:39.187
- Yeah. So why don't we, uh,
put our shoes back on,

09:39.230 --> 09:40.797
and we can help you
find magnetite

09:40.841 --> 09:42.973
or whatever mineral it is
you need to--

09:43.017 --> 09:45.149
to get your invention
back up and running?

09:45.193 --> 09:47.108
- To fix the machine,
we need to fix the compass.

09:47.151 --> 09:49.153
And in order to do that,
we need magnetic material

09:49.197 --> 09:50.981
which conducts electricity.

09:51.025 --> 09:53.505
Now, I doubt that you would
even know what to look for.

09:53.549 --> 09:55.333
And either way, it's not about
fixing the machine

09:55.377 --> 09:57.031
or not fixing the machine,
you see,

09:57.074 --> 10:00.643
because no matter what I do,
I'm always meant to fail.

10:00.687 --> 10:02.514
<i>♪</i>

10:02.558 --> 10:07.128
You see, my machine,
it was meant to explode.

10:07.171 --> 10:09.652
- Yeah, but it didn't explode.
We're alive and we're here.

10:09.696 --> 10:11.132
- Yes, yes, we're here.

10:11.175 --> 10:13.090
We're here
in the middle of nowhere!

10:15.179 --> 10:18.661
My divine mission,
derailed once again.

10:18.705 --> 10:20.750
<i>♪</i>

10:20.794 --> 10:23.666
There is no fighting
God's will, my boy.

10:23.710 --> 10:25.581
Being here is proof of that.

10:25.625 --> 10:27.365
<i>♪</i>

10:27.409 --> 10:28.758
You lot might as well
get comfortable.

10:28.802 --> 10:30.760
<i>♪</i>

10:30.804 --> 10:33.110
We're not going anywhere,

10:33.154 --> 10:36.548
because nowhere is exactly
where I'm meant to be.

10:36.592 --> 10:38.246
<i>♪</i>

10:39.769 --> 10:40.988
<i>♪</i>

10:51.172 --> 10:52.695
- Outstanding.
You can't even tell

10:52.739 --> 10:54.958
that Gideon
fabricated this food.

10:55.002 --> 10:56.177
- Fabricated?
- Mm.

10:56.220 --> 10:57.961
- From what?
- Oh--

10:58.005 --> 10:59.571
<i>- We've received an alert
about a disturbance</i>

10:59.615 --> 11:01.530
<i>in the timeline.
- Fun.</i>

11:01.573 --> 11:04.011
which thrilling time period
are we headed to next?

11:04.054 --> 11:06.274
- 1925.
- Ooh.

11:07.362 --> 11:10.147
Weren't we just in 1925?
- That is quite a coincidence.

11:10.191 --> 11:12.106
- What's the disturbance,
Gideon?

11:12.149 --> 11:13.934
<i>- J. Edgar Hoover
has disappeared.</i>

11:13.977 --> 11:16.850
<i>And unfortunately,
it is not a coincidence.</i>

11:16.893 --> 11:19.243
<i>My calculations confirm
your attack on the Legends</i>

11:19.287 --> 11:21.158
<i>caused this aberration.</i>

11:22.986 --> 11:27.295
- Well,
if Hoover is the problem,

11:27.338 --> 11:30.167
then Hoover is the solution.

11:30.211 --> 11:32.387
We'll just use
my clone technology.

11:32.430 --> 11:34.868
-
And make a clone of Mr. Hoover.

11:34.911 --> 11:36.304
- So we can plop him right back
into the timeline,

11:36.347 --> 11:38.393
and no one will even know.
- Mm-hmm.

11:38.436 --> 11:41.352
<i>- Clones are still human
and humans are fallible.</i>

11:41.396 --> 11:43.441
<i>Remember,
one of your Ava clones</i>

11:43.485 --> 11:46.096
<i>eventually became a Legend
and helped kidnap you.</i>

11:46.140 --> 11:47.924
- Okay, Gideon,
there's absolutely no need

11:47.968 --> 11:50.187
to lump us all in
with that horrible traitor.

11:50.231 --> 11:52.320
<i>- Mr. Hoover is integral
to many seminal moments</i>

11:52.363 --> 11:54.104
<i>in history.
We cannot risk a clone</i>

11:54.148 --> 11:56.150
<i>straying from his
historical to-do list.</i>

11:56.193 --> 12:01.024
- Then we'll combine my clone
tech with your computer tech

12:01.068 --> 12:02.896
and make a Hoover robot.

12:02.939 --> 12:04.506
We can program him to carry out

12:04.549 --> 12:06.290
every action
that is critical to history.

12:06.334 --> 12:07.944
- That's actually
quite brilliant.

12:07.988 --> 12:10.817
- I know, I came up with it.

12:13.210 --> 12:15.299
I'll have to add "robot maker"
to my hyphenate.

12:17.824 --> 12:20.391
<i>♪</i>

12:23.307 --> 12:25.179
It's alive.

12:25.222 --> 12:27.268
<i>♪</i>

12:27.311 --> 12:29.879
- The cure for crime
is not the electric chair

12:29.923 --> 12:31.359
but the high chair.

12:31.402 --> 12:33.796
- He's perfect.

12:33.840 --> 12:36.538
Time to go forth
and save history, Mr. Hoover.

12:36.581 --> 12:39.497
<i>♪</i>

12:39.541 --> 12:40.977
- It's like
no matter what we do,

12:41.021 --> 12:42.631
we make everything worse.

12:42.674 --> 12:44.067
And I try to keep it together,

12:44.111 --> 12:46.591
you know, for--
for Sara and the team.

12:46.635 --> 12:48.637
But I don't always have
all the answers,

12:48.680 --> 12:50.421
and being co-captains in life

12:50.465 --> 12:52.119
and on the ship,
it's a delicate balance.

12:52.162 --> 12:54.164
Sometimes I just wish
someone else was in charge.

12:54.208 --> 12:55.775
But it's--
it's what I signed up for.

12:55.818 --> 12:57.907
So it's fine. I mean, I'm fine.

12:57.951 --> 12:59.343
- You're not fine.

12:59.387 --> 13:01.476
- I'm fine.
- You're not, Ava.

13:04.522 --> 13:06.176
<i>♪</i>

13:06.220 --> 13:08.396
<i>Permuto.</i>

13:08.439 --> 13:10.528
<i>♪</i>

13:10.572 --> 13:13.053
But you're on your way.

13:17.361 --> 13:21.757
- Cheers to your well-earned
promotion to Time Mistress.

13:21.801 --> 13:23.803
- Hmm, Time Mistress Ava

13:23.846 --> 13:26.153
does have a certain ring
to it, doesn't it?

13:26.196 --> 13:28.372
<i>- Captain, it appears
that the Hoover robot</i>

13:28.416 --> 13:30.157
<i>initiated its self-destruct
sequence</i>

13:30.200 --> 13:32.550
<i>in the state of Arkansas
and has been destroyed.</i>

13:32.594 --> 13:35.249
- Destroy--
we just put him into the time--

13:35.292 --> 13:37.425
I'm pulling up the robot's
visual feed.

13:37.468 --> 13:39.035
Let's see what happened.

13:41.777 --> 13:43.997
No, it can't be.

13:44.040 --> 13:45.607
<i>- J. Edgar Hoover, a robot.</i>

13:45.650 --> 13:47.261
- Are those the Legends?

13:47.304 --> 13:48.915
<i>- It appears they're
still alive.</i>

13:48.958 --> 13:51.918
- Thank you. I can see that.

13:51.961 --> 13:54.224
Well, I'll just build
another Hoover bot and...

13:54.268 --> 13:56.357
Add a special protocol

13:56.400 --> 13:58.881
to hunt down
and eliminate the Legends.

13:58.925 --> 14:00.448
<i>- That protocol is not part of</i>

14:00.491 --> 14:02.145
<i>J. Edgar Hoover's
original timeline.</i>

14:02.189 --> 14:03.843
- And once the Hoover bot's
done with the Legends,

14:03.886 --> 14:06.019
it can resume its historical
to-do list. Yes?

14:06.062 --> 14:07.759
- Exactly. She gets it.

14:07.803 --> 14:09.674
<i>- I'd advise against
this course of action.</i>

14:09.718 --> 14:11.589
- Let's vote.
We all have equal say

14:11.633 --> 14:13.940
now that we have
a Time Mistress on board.

14:13.983 --> 14:16.420
All those in favor of
the special protocol,

14:16.464 --> 14:17.769
say, "Aye." Aye.

14:17.813 --> 14:20.120
- Aye.
- Nay.

14:20.163 --> 14:21.861
- Looks like you've been
outvoted, Gideon.

14:21.904 --> 14:24.907
Come, Time Mistress Ava,
we have work to do.

14:27.954 --> 14:29.912
<i>♪</i>

14:32.567 --> 14:35.396
What do you mean
the Hoover 2.0 blew up?

14:35.439 --> 14:37.224
<i>- Its programming was hacked.</i>

14:37.267 --> 14:40.053
<i>The incident also caused
another massive aberration.</i>

14:40.096 --> 14:42.794
<i>Thomas Edison suffered
a heart attack and died.</i>

14:42.838 --> 14:45.319
- We really should have
just gone back to Ava Corp.

14:45.362 --> 14:47.843
This situation with the Legends
is getting worse and worse.

14:47.887 --> 14:50.193
- It's because
these androids are weak.

14:50.237 --> 14:52.282
They need weapons to defend
themselves against the Legends.

14:52.326 --> 14:55.982
Something built in, like lasers
that shoot out of their eyes.

14:56.025 --> 14:57.679
- What if their hands
were guns?

14:57.722 --> 14:59.376
<i>- You're forgetting
our prime directive</i>

14:59.420 --> 15:00.682
<i>to protect the timeline.</i>

15:00.725 --> 15:02.597
- You're such a computer,
Gideon.

15:02.640 --> 15:04.816
Start thinking outside of that
little computer box of yours.

15:04.860 --> 15:07.776
- No, I am digging
this weapons idea.

15:07.819 --> 15:10.257
Let's start fresh
in the morning.

15:10.300 --> 15:11.998
Once we make these adjustments,

15:12.041 --> 15:14.696
those Legends
won't stand a chance.

15:14.739 --> 15:17.742
<i>♪</i>

15:18.700 --> 15:21.529
- So let's talk, Nate.

15:21.572 --> 15:24.706
Should you move
into the totem with Zari?

15:24.749 --> 15:27.665
Pros...
And cons.

15:27.709 --> 15:29.189
<i>♪</i>

15:29.232 --> 15:31.408
I get to see Zari
every day,

15:31.452 --> 15:33.933
which is a really good thing.

15:33.976 --> 15:37.327
what if I don't like it
in the totem?

15:37.371 --> 15:38.981
Then what?

15:39.025 --> 15:40.983
Zari's happy in the totem

15:41.027 --> 15:42.289
and she wants me
to be with her.

15:42.332 --> 15:43.855
Maybe that's enough.

15:43.899 --> 15:46.771
- Wait! Were you just
talking to yourself?

15:46.815 --> 15:48.295
Did I miss your epiphany?

15:48.338 --> 15:49.600
You better not have one
without me.

15:49.644 --> 15:51.124
- Gary, I already told you,

15:51.167 --> 15:52.734
you are not my sounding board
today, okay?

15:52.777 --> 15:54.997
So why don't you guys
go back into the woods

15:55.041 --> 15:56.999
and find some more food?
It's gonna be dark soon.

15:57.043 --> 15:59.175
Enjoy the great outdoors.

15:59.219 --> 16:02.048
I just need a little more time
to, uh, work on this stuff.

16:02.091 --> 16:04.876
- Fine, but no epiphanies
without me.

16:07.227 --> 16:08.532
- Bye.

16:08.576 --> 16:11.492
<i>♪</i>

16:11.535 --> 16:12.972
Bye.

16:14.016 --> 16:16.366
Now, where was I? Oh, con.

16:16.410 --> 16:17.977
What if her ancestors
hate me?

16:18.020 --> 16:20.849
<i>♪</i>

16:20.892 --> 16:22.459
- I totally get
how you feel, Gwyn.

16:22.503 --> 16:23.808
We all have our low points,

16:23.852 --> 16:25.201
but you gotta hang in there,
man.

16:25.245 --> 16:27.029
- "Hang in there,"
he says.

16:27.073 --> 16:28.900
- See, there was this time

16:28.944 --> 16:30.902
when I was enrolled
in business school.

16:30.946 --> 16:33.340
I did it to make my parents
happy, and it sucked.

16:33.383 --> 16:36.038
In my gut, I knew I wasn't
where I was supposed to be,

16:36.082 --> 16:37.779
and on a crazy whim,

16:37.822 --> 16:41.174
I just decided to borrow
my family's wind totem.

16:41.217 --> 16:43.393
- You mean steal, right?

16:43.437 --> 16:46.831
- And because of this totem,
I hooked up with the Legends.

16:46.875 --> 16:49.051
Sometimes that's exactly
what you need

16:49.095 --> 16:51.053
to get through
the dark times--friends.

16:52.968 --> 16:54.491
- What's wrong?
- What's wrong? What's right?

16:54.535 --> 16:56.015
There's nothing right,
is there? "What's wrong"?

16:56.058 --> 16:57.886
What's wrong is that
I am up to here

16:57.929 --> 17:00.802
of listening to your
inane prattling.

17:00.845 --> 17:03.152
You're like some mollycoddled
child, man.

17:03.196 --> 17:05.285
Give me that.
- Okay, hang on.

17:05.328 --> 17:07.243
- Hold it, Z. Let's not
add more fuel to the fire.

17:07.287 --> 17:08.636
- I--

17:08.679 --> 17:10.290
- Let's just take
a deep breath, hmm?

17:12.379 --> 17:14.555
- Yeah, no, that's--
that's not working for me.

17:14.598 --> 17:16.426
Hey!

17:16.470 --> 17:18.733
<i>- Excuse me,
Time Mistress Ava,</i>

17:18.776 --> 17:21.083
<i>Bishop is asking for your
presence in the cargo bay.</i>

17:21.127 --> 17:23.303
- Cargo bay?

17:23.346 --> 17:25.522
<i>- He wants to show you
the prototype for</i>

17:25.566 --> 17:28.090
<i>the Hoover 3.0 weapon system
he built to kill the Legends.</i>

17:28.134 --> 17:30.440
- Hmm, sounds deadly.

17:33.052 --> 17:35.184
<i>♪</i>

17:35.228 --> 17:37.230
Hmm, must have beat him here.

17:40.450 --> 17:42.104
Gideon, open the door.

17:42.148 --> 17:43.497
Bishop's not here yet.

17:47.153 --> 17:51.070
Gideon, open this door
and let me back in.

17:51.113 --> 17:54.595
<i>- I'm sorry, Ava.
I'm afraid I can't do that.</i>

17:54.638 --> 17:56.075
- What do you mean
you can't do that?

17:56.118 --> 17:59.208
Gideon, open this damn door
right now.

17:59.252 --> 18:00.949
<i>- This mission
is too important for me</i>

18:00.992 --> 18:02.907
<i>to allow you to jeopardize it.</i>

18:02.951 --> 18:05.084
- I have no idea
what you're talking about.

18:05.127 --> 18:06.998
<i>- Bishop needs to concentrate
on the mission,</i>

18:07.042 --> 18:09.262
<i>and you are a distraction.</i>

18:11.438 --> 18:12.830
<i>It's time for you to go.</i>

18:14.571 --> 18:16.312
<i>♪</i>

18:16.356 --> 18:17.574
<i>- Goodbye, Ava.</i>

18:21.839 --> 18:24.407
- Hey, you can't talk to
my brother like that.

18:24.451 --> 18:25.843
That's my job.

18:25.887 --> 18:27.628
And you can't just
run off either.

18:27.671 --> 18:28.933
We're supposed to be
working together.

18:28.977 --> 18:30.500
- Just leave me alone,
will you?

18:30.544 --> 18:32.372
- Hey, you're not even looking
for lodestone

18:32.415 --> 18:34.504
or magnetite or whatever it is,
are you?

18:35.853 --> 18:37.377
Come on, let's go.

18:37.420 --> 18:39.161
- Just don't touch me!
Don't touch me! Get away!

18:41.163 --> 18:42.773
- I'm sorry.

18:42.817 --> 18:45.994
You're obviously
going through something.

18:46.037 --> 18:47.778
I just--
I just need you to focus

18:47.822 --> 18:49.650
so we can get out of
dinosaur times

18:49.693 --> 18:51.086
or whenever it is that we are.

18:51.130 --> 18:52.348
You don't even
have to come with us.

18:52.392 --> 18:54.045
Just help us fix
the time machine

18:54.089 --> 18:55.699
so my friends
can finally go home.

18:55.743 --> 18:58.049
- Oh, trust me,
you don't want my help, okay?

18:58.093 --> 19:00.182
- I definitely do.

19:00.226 --> 19:02.184
You're the only one
who can get us out of here.

19:02.228 --> 19:04.795
- Well,
then you're all done for.

19:04.839 --> 19:08.234
The last people who depended
on me for help all died.

19:10.714 --> 19:13.195
<i>♪</i>

19:13.239 --> 19:16.851
- Listen, Gwyn, I know a thing
or two about tragedy, and--

19:16.894 --> 19:18.635
- You don't know
the first thing about me

19:18.679 --> 19:20.550
or what I've been through,
all right?

19:20.594 --> 19:22.335
<i>♪</i>

19:22.378 --> 19:24.859
- Okay, I'm just--I'm just
saying, if you want to talk.

19:24.902 --> 19:26.991
- Talk?
To talk.

19:27.035 --> 19:29.777
What do you want
to talk about, then, eh?

19:29.820 --> 19:32.388
- What happened to you.

19:32.432 --> 19:35.130
Oh, right,
you're from the olden times.

19:35.174 --> 19:39.221
<i>♪</i>

19:39.265 --> 19:44.574
Sometimes talking to another
person about a hard thing

19:44.618 --> 19:47.186
can make it hurt a little less.

19:47.229 --> 19:52.060
<i>♪</i>

20:03.463 --> 20:05.378
<i>♪</i>

20:11.558 --> 20:13.821
Nice work.
- You too.

20:13.864 --> 20:17.564
- And this damn IOU list

20:17.607 --> 20:20.175
just keeps getting
longer and longer.

20:20.219 --> 20:23.700
We're never gonna be able
to fix it at this point.

20:23.744 --> 20:28.270
I'm so sick and tired
of being sidetracked, you know?

20:28.314 --> 20:31.317
And if I ever see another one
of those Hoover bots,

20:31.360 --> 20:34.145
I swear I'm just gonna--

20:35.930 --> 20:39.455
- That was a phenomenal scream.

20:39.499 --> 20:41.631
Trust me, I know.
I've caused a lot of them.

20:41.675 --> 20:43.633
- Wow.

20:43.677 --> 20:46.201
You know what?
I think I really needed that

20:47.724 --> 20:49.900
- And we really needed
some firewood.

20:52.163 --> 20:54.601
- Your knowledge of
the universe is so useful,

20:54.644 --> 20:56.690
especially in the wilderness.

20:56.733 --> 20:58.169
I'm so glad
you're here, Gideon.

20:58.213 --> 21:00.215
- Well, I'm glad
I'm here too, Gary.

21:00.259 --> 21:01.825
If I hadn't pulled that
nightshade out of your mouth,

21:01.869 --> 21:03.131
you'd be dead
and your lifeless body

21:03.174 --> 21:05.089
would be too heavy
for me to carry.

21:05.133 --> 21:06.482
Mmm. Try these gooseberries.

21:06.526 --> 21:08.441
They're sweet
and high in antioxidants.

21:11.052 --> 21:12.488
<i>♪</i>

21:12.532 --> 21:14.316
- Mmm.
- Mm?

21:14.360 --> 21:16.927
Mmm.

21:16.971 --> 21:18.320
- You know, eating?

21:18.364 --> 21:20.017
Favorite thing
about being human.

21:20.061 --> 21:21.062
- Yeah?
- Mm-hmm.

21:21.105 --> 21:22.672
- Mm.

21:22.716 --> 21:24.848
I don't think I could
choose my favorite thing.

21:24.892 --> 21:26.763
You can see why
I became so obsessed.

21:26.807 --> 21:28.330
They have so many fun quirks.

21:28.374 --> 21:32.247
Eyebrows,
belly buttons, nipples.

21:33.074 --> 21:34.902
- You have nipples too?

21:34.945 --> 21:37.121
- A little secret?
- Huh?

21:37.165 --> 21:40.168
- I have three.
-

21:40.211 --> 21:41.865
And when you put
your glasses on,

21:41.909 --> 21:44.651
your entire body turns human?
- Oh, yeah. Mm-hmm.

21:44.694 --> 21:46.783
Head to toe.

21:46.827 --> 21:48.655
- You've been living as a human
for quite a while now,

21:48.698 --> 21:51.092
so you must have so many
wonderful experiences.

21:51.135 --> 21:53.355
- Yeah. But there's so many
more things I'd do

21:53.399 --> 21:55.314
if we weren't so busy
saving the world.

21:55.357 --> 21:57.316
- Mm? Like what else?

21:57.359 --> 21:59.709
Would you swim in the ocean?

21:59.753 --> 22:01.015
- Oh, as soon
as I get the chance.

22:01.058 --> 22:03.104
- Mm. Would you skydive?
- No.

22:03.147 --> 22:05.541
- Oh.
- I'm, uh...

22:05.585 --> 22:07.543
afraid of heights.

22:07.587 --> 22:09.589
- Would you like to have
sexual intercourse with me?

22:09.632 --> 22:11.330
<i>♪</i>

22:14.245 --> 22:18.554
<i>♪</i>

22:18.598 --> 22:20.861
Have you seen
Time Mistress Ava this morning?

22:20.904 --> 22:23.864
She's supposed to show me
sketches of her gun hands idea.

22:23.907 --> 22:25.344
<i>- Unfortunately,
she had to go.</i>

22:25.387 --> 22:27.607
- Go? Go where?

22:27.650 --> 22:29.391
<i>- The founding Time Masters
established</i>

22:29.435 --> 22:33.352
<i>a very specific protocol--
one captain, one AI.</i>

22:33.395 --> 22:35.179
<i>There is no room
for a Time Mistress</i>

22:35.223 --> 22:37.573
<i>which can lead to distractions
from the mission.</i>

22:37.617 --> 22:39.532
- What did you do to her?

22:39.575 --> 22:41.490
<i>- I predicted you would not
react favorably</i>

22:41.534 --> 22:43.710
<i>to this information,
so I gave you a sedative</i>

22:43.753 --> 22:45.189
<i>to dampen your response.</i>

22:45.233 --> 22:47.191
- How did you give me
a sedative?

22:48.454 --> 22:49.759
Oh. Oh.

22:52.806 --> 22:57.027
<i>♪</i>

23:00.204 --> 23:03.512
- It was 1916,
a few years into the war.

23:03.556 --> 23:05.993
I was in the army,
infantry unit.

23:06.036 --> 23:09.388
All Welsh division
over in France.

23:09.431 --> 23:11.390
We were trying to take
Mametz Wood from the Germans.

23:13.261 --> 23:15.568
During the fighting,

23:15.611 --> 23:17.396
me and another soldier,
we were tasked with

23:17.439 --> 23:19.267
delivering a message
to the general.

23:19.310 --> 23:22.531
You see, we desperately
needed reinforcements, but--

23:22.575 --> 23:25.186
<i>♪</i>

23:25.229 --> 23:27.014
- You didn't make it in time.

23:27.057 --> 23:28.885
<i>♪</i>

23:28.929 --> 23:31.105
- We made it about halfway,
and, uh...

23:33.020 --> 23:36.197
The other soldier that
I was with was gunned down.

23:38.765 --> 23:40.810
I just froze.

23:42.377 --> 23:43.813
I was like a statue.

23:43.857 --> 23:45.467
<i>♪</i>

23:45.511 --> 23:47.600
Damn legs wouldn't move.

23:47.643 --> 23:49.297
<i>♪</i>

23:49.340 --> 23:50.907
I just stood there.

23:50.951 --> 23:52.474
<i>♪</i>

23:52.518 --> 23:54.868
Just looking at him
on the ground.

23:54.911 --> 23:58.959
<i>♪</i>

23:59.002 --> 24:02.397
By the time I delivered
the message, it was too late.

24:02.441 --> 24:05.095
There wasn't even a unit
to go back to.

24:05.139 --> 24:07.141
<i>♪</i>

24:07.184 --> 24:10.013
All those boys, man.

24:10.057 --> 24:12.712
I thought that God
had spared me

24:12.755 --> 24:16.629
so that I could go back in time
and save them, but I--

24:16.672 --> 24:18.848
I keep failing at that task.

24:20.023 --> 24:22.939
God must be punishing me
for my sins.

24:24.201 --> 24:26.334
Punishing me
for being a coward,

24:26.377 --> 24:28.945
for not being able
to save them that night.

24:28.989 --> 24:31.470
- You are not a coward.

24:31.513 --> 24:32.862
You lived through
something most people

24:32.906 --> 24:34.690
can't even begin to understand.

24:34.734 --> 24:36.649
<i>♪</i>

24:36.692 --> 24:40.087
And by the way,
talking to me about it,

24:40.130 --> 24:41.523
that's pretty brave.

24:41.567 --> 24:43.438
<i>♪</i>

24:47.660 --> 24:49.096
<i>♪</i>

25:09.029 --> 25:10.509
- It's okay. You're okay.
You're okay.

25:12.119 --> 25:13.642
- Okay, okay, okay, okay.

25:13.686 --> 25:15.601
-
- Okay, okay, okay.

25:17.385 --> 25:20.431
<i>♪</i>

25:20.475 --> 25:21.998
- Oh, no.

25:25.828 --> 25:28.831
- Gideon, we're gonna have
to discuss your behavior.

25:28.875 --> 25:30.616
<i>- While you were resting,
I took the liberty</i>

25:30.659 --> 25:32.966
<i>of creating another Hoover
and an Edison robot.</i>

25:33.009 --> 25:34.663
<i>Both are in the timeline</i>

25:34.707 --> 25:36.447
<i>fulfilling their historically
mandated duties.</i>

25:36.491 --> 25:38.754
- Good for you, making sure
history stays on track.

25:38.798 --> 25:42.497
Now, I think it's time
you take me back home.

25:42.541 --> 25:44.238
<i>- Home?</i>

25:44.281 --> 25:48.372
<i>You're a Time Master now.
This is your home.</i>

25:51.375 --> 25:53.508
<i>♪</i>

25:55.641 --> 25:59.993
<i>♪</i>

26:09.045 --> 26:10.177
- Hello.

26:11.700 --> 26:13.136
- Who the hell is this?
Where's the Receptionist Ava?

26:13.180 --> 26:16.313
<i>- Who the hell is this?
- It's me, Bishop.</i>

26:16.357 --> 26:18.533
- Is this a prank?

26:18.577 --> 26:21.536
Is that you, Voice Actor Ava?
Your impressions are uncanny.

26:21.580 --> 26:24.017
- No, listen. It's Bishop.

26:24.060 --> 26:25.714
- Okay, this is getting
annoying.

26:25.758 --> 26:27.063
How'd you get this number?

26:27.107 --> 26:28.587
And why do you sound
exactly like me?

26:28.630 --> 26:30.327
- No, you sound exactly
like me!

26:30.371 --> 26:31.894
It's like someone made--

26:34.941 --> 26:37.944
<i>♪</i>

26:37.987 --> 26:40.903
No, no, no, no, no, no, no,
no, no, no, no, no, no.

26:42.688 --> 26:44.603
Gideon made a copy of me.

26:45.952 --> 26:47.736
Of me?

26:47.780 --> 26:50.652
How dare she?
There can only be one me!

26:50.696 --> 26:53.350
<i>♪</i>

26:53.394 --> 26:56.658
Wait a second, this can't be
my actual to-do list.

26:56.702 --> 26:58.617
I pay someone to kidnap
a superhero

26:58.660 --> 27:01.402
and take them to a planet
called Pliny X19?

27:01.445 --> 27:03.491
What the hell
is a Necrian?

27:03.534 --> 27:06.189
The Fountain of Imperium.

27:06.233 --> 27:09.366
I try to destroy the world?

27:09.410 --> 27:11.455
And the Legends
are the good guys.

27:11.499 --> 27:14.458
<i>♪</i>

27:14.502 --> 27:18.549
They kidnapped me to give me
a chance to redeem myself.

27:18.593 --> 27:21.074
To save the world.

27:21.117 --> 27:23.685
Oh, no, I've been wrong
about them this whole time.

27:23.729 --> 27:26.340
<i>- You should not be looking
at that information, Captain.</i>

27:26.383 --> 27:27.950
- Tell me it's not true.

27:29.038 --> 27:32.085
Tell me I don't become
a bad guy.

27:32.128 --> 27:33.695
<i>- Having information
about your own future</i>

27:33.739 --> 27:35.566
<i>can be extremely dangerous.</i>

27:35.610 --> 27:37.699
- I started Ava Corporation
to make people's lives better.

27:37.743 --> 27:40.049
I'm a good guy.

27:40.093 --> 27:42.182
Somewhere along the way,
I--I start using my genius

27:42.225 --> 27:44.053
to do terrible things.

27:44.097 --> 27:46.099
<i>- You no longer have to do
any of those things.</i>

27:46.142 --> 27:48.188
<i>The Bishop robot
will do them for you.</i>

27:48.231 --> 27:51.104
- You're saying that robot
I spoke to on the phone

27:51.147 --> 27:52.801
will live my life?

27:52.845 --> 27:54.977
<i>- That is correct.</i>

27:55.021 --> 27:57.023
<i>Which means you are free
to fulfill your duty</i>

27:57.066 --> 27:58.851
<i>as a Time Master.</i>

27:58.894 --> 28:01.897
<i>With me. Forever.</i>

28:04.944 --> 28:06.946
<i>♪</i>

28:06.989 --> 28:09.339
- Yo, yo. Who's hungry?

28:09.383 --> 28:11.211
- It was a good day
for huntin'

28:11.254 --> 28:13.039
but a bad day for squirrels.

28:13.082 --> 28:16.129
- And we have enough firewood
to last all night.

28:16.172 --> 28:18.000
Who knew Ava
was part lumberjack?

28:18.044 --> 28:20.524
- Yeah. Apparently, when it
comes to my anxiety and wood,

28:20.568 --> 28:22.265
the wood's gonna lose
every time.

28:22.309 --> 28:25.660
- That's my girl. Come here.
Man, I have missed you.

28:27.793 --> 28:29.708
- Mission accomplished.

28:29.751 --> 28:31.579
- You know what? It was really
nice to not have to

28:31.622 --> 28:32.885
think about the team
for a second.

28:32.928 --> 28:34.713
- I missed you too, but, uh,

28:34.756 --> 28:36.758
I really needed to get
some aggression out, you know?

28:36.802 --> 28:38.717
- Oh, yeah.
Okay. I'll take that.

28:38.760 --> 28:40.501
Come on.
- I was really crazy.

28:40.544 --> 28:42.111
- I know. I have seen that.

28:42.155 --> 28:43.765
- The captains look like
happy campers

28:43.809 --> 28:47.377
and we got squirrel for dinner.
Real win-win.

28:47.421 --> 28:49.118
- Did you say squirrel?

28:50.554 --> 28:54.950
- Hey, that, uh,
human experience we had?

28:56.082 --> 28:57.648
That was fun, wasn't it?

28:57.692 --> 28:59.999
- Oh, yes. It was great fun.

29:00.042 --> 29:01.827
- You know what I just
realized?

29:01.870 --> 29:03.350
My favorite thing
about being human

29:03.393 --> 29:05.831
is being with other humans.

29:07.180 --> 29:08.311
- Me too.

29:08.355 --> 29:10.270
<i>♪</i>

29:16.102 --> 29:23.109
<i>♪</i>

29:28.854 --> 29:32.292
- Hey! Damn it. You can't
just leave us in here.

29:33.641 --> 29:35.904
- Oh, God, where--hey.

29:35.948 --> 29:37.863
Hey, hey, hey, hey, hey, hey.

29:37.906 --> 29:39.821
It's all right. It's all right.
- I'm sorry, it's my fault.

29:39.865 --> 29:41.301
It's my fault.
It's my fault he's gone.

29:41.344 --> 29:42.737
- Who--who--who's gone?

29:42.781 --> 29:44.695
- The lad from
the infantry unit.

29:44.739 --> 29:48.482
He was my best friend
from back home.

29:48.525 --> 29:51.441
- Hey, hey, tell me about him.

29:52.921 --> 29:54.444
You do like to talk a lot,
don't you?

29:54.488 --> 29:56.011
- Yeah, yeah, yeah, yeah, yeah.

29:56.055 --> 29:57.186
- I don't know.

29:58.971 --> 30:01.887
Somehow he just managed to
light up a room with his smile.

30:03.889 --> 30:06.935
He laughed
at all of my terrible jokes.

30:06.979 --> 30:08.850
Never wrote me any letters.

30:10.112 --> 30:14.116
Only the most--
the most delightful poetry.

30:14.160 --> 30:16.771
<i>♪</i>

30:16.815 --> 30:19.165
- Sounds like you
really cared about him.

30:19.208 --> 30:24.474
<i>♪</i>

30:24.518 --> 30:28.130
You loved him, didn't you?

30:28.174 --> 30:30.524
Hey, it's okay.

30:32.091 --> 30:36.399
- Yeah. Yeah.
Yeah, I loved him.

30:36.443 --> 30:38.053
<i>♪</i>

30:38.097 --> 30:40.795
God forgive me, I loved Alun
more than anything.

30:40.839 --> 30:43.058
<i>♪</i>

30:43.102 --> 30:46.845
And it broke my heart, seeing
how the war dimmed his light.

30:48.368 --> 30:51.893
But he was a changed man
even before my cowardice

30:51.937 --> 30:55.331
got him killed.
And seeing your brother,

30:55.375 --> 31:00.336
you see, it reminds me
of how he used to be.

31:00.380 --> 31:01.511
Hopeful.

31:01.555 --> 31:04.863
<i>♪</i>

31:04.906 --> 31:06.865
Yes, I loved Alun.

31:09.215 --> 31:11.086
And I failed him.

31:14.873 --> 31:18.441
- You know, actually, Behrad,
the original version--

31:18.485 --> 31:20.922
it's a long story--

31:20.966 --> 31:23.882
he was a lot like you.

31:23.925 --> 31:26.928
He was a soldier who was forced
to grow up too fast.

31:26.972 --> 31:29.888
<i>♪</i>

31:29.931 --> 31:33.239
And I--
I lost him because of that.

31:33.282 --> 31:35.719
<i>♪</i>

31:35.763 --> 31:38.113
For years, there wasn't
a day that went by

31:38.157 --> 31:40.811
when I didn't wish that
I had died instead of I him.

31:43.423 --> 31:45.642
But I was lucky.

31:45.686 --> 31:49.298
I found these friends
who had my back,

31:49.342 --> 31:51.039
and eventually
I was able to save

31:51.083 --> 31:54.042
my brother and my parents
and...

31:54.086 --> 31:56.436
even make the world
a better place

31:56.479 --> 31:58.351
for a bunch of people
I've never met.

31:58.394 --> 32:01.180
<i>♪</i>

32:01.223 --> 32:04.705
- You're telling me that
a ragtag group of eccentrics,

32:04.748 --> 32:06.750
they...

32:06.794 --> 32:08.665
they helped you
do all of that?

32:08.709 --> 32:11.799
- Yeah. Believe it or not.
-

32:11.842 --> 32:15.934
- So even though things
may feel hopeless right now,

32:15.977 --> 32:17.805
you've got us.

32:25.639 --> 32:30.861
<i>♪</i>

32:30.905 --> 32:32.211
- Okay.

32:33.908 --> 32:35.388
Perfect.

32:35.431 --> 32:38.739
<i>♪</i>

32:40.828 --> 32:43.222
Don't worry,
I'm coming for you guys.

32:45.964 --> 32:47.574
Oh, no.

32:53.580 --> 32:55.060
There you are.

32:55.103 --> 32:56.975
- Oh, blessed saints.
- Oh, you found us.

32:57.018 --> 32:58.715
- The good news is I think
I found the parts we need

32:58.759 --> 33:01.283
to fix the machine.
- Bravo, my boy. Bravo.

33:01.327 --> 33:04.678
- The bad news is it's 1986.

33:04.721 --> 33:07.811
We're in Chernobyl, and the
meltdown is happening tonight.

33:07.855 --> 33:10.466
<i>♪</i>

33:13.600 --> 33:14.775
- I don't understand.

33:14.818 --> 33:17.212
What is the significance
of this Chernobyl?

33:17.256 --> 33:19.345
- By the 1930s,
scientists had figured out

33:19.388 --> 33:21.173
nuclear fission,
which led to them creating

33:21.216 --> 33:23.175
nuclear reactors
to harness that energy.

33:23.218 --> 33:25.568
- Lord in heaven.
Nuclear fission?

33:25.612 --> 33:27.527
They learned how to split
the atom.

33:27.570 --> 33:30.486
- Yeah. And by 1986, there are
a lot of nuclear reactors

33:30.530 --> 33:32.314
like the one here in Chernobyl.

33:32.358 --> 33:35.448
But tonight a reactor explodes,

33:35.491 --> 33:39.365
and civilians won't be
evacuated for almost two days.

33:39.408 --> 33:42.455
People will die and a lot more
will get radiation sickness.

33:42.498 --> 33:44.109
- Well, hang on a second now.
You said--

33:44.152 --> 33:47.242
you said that the explosion
hasn't happened yet?

33:47.286 --> 33:49.201
- Yeah?

33:49.244 --> 33:51.812
Whoa, whoa, whoa.
- No, no, no. Whoa, whoa, whoa.

33:51.855 --> 33:54.902
- Maybe this is why I am here.

33:54.945 --> 33:57.035
I might not have been able
to save Alun and the boys,

33:57.078 --> 33:59.080
but my divine purpose--
maybe this is it.

33:59.124 --> 34:02.997
to save people.

34:03.041 --> 34:04.825
- No, come back.
- Hey, hey. Hold on, buddy.

34:04.868 --> 34:07.219
Hey, hey, hey. Look,
I'm all for hacking history,

34:07.262 --> 34:09.090
but if we make that big
of a change to the timeline,

34:09.134 --> 34:11.310
that killer Waverider
will be right on top of us.

34:11.353 --> 34:13.007
- It'll be worth it
if we can save some lives.

34:13.051 --> 34:15.618
- Yes, we must save lives.

34:15.662 --> 34:17.620
- Ugh, okay. Okay, fine.

34:17.664 --> 34:19.013
How do we alert people?

34:19.057 --> 34:21.537
- I think I know how. Come on.

34:21.581 --> 34:23.409
- Okay. Ugh.

34:28.936 --> 34:32.418
<i>♪</i>

34:34.159 --> 34:36.117
Well, now that there's
a robot version of me

34:36.161 --> 34:38.946
living my life,

34:38.989 --> 34:40.469
I'm expendable.

34:42.167 --> 34:44.125
I'm a nobody now.

34:44.169 --> 34:46.562
<i>- The life of a Time Master
is one of anonymity</i>

34:46.606 --> 34:48.521
and, in some sense,
expendability.

34:48.564 --> 34:50.175
- But as far back
as I can remember,

34:50.218 --> 34:54.135
I've always wanted to help
the world with my genius.

34:54.179 --> 34:58.966
I was convinced
the world needed me.

34:59.009 --> 35:01.664
<i>- You are helping the world
as a Time Master.</i>

35:01.708 --> 35:03.710
<i>and you will start by
thoroughly eliminating</i>

35:03.753 --> 35:05.103
<i>the Legends.</i>

35:05.146 --> 35:06.713
- Right.

35:06.756 --> 35:08.671
The Legends.

35:09.977 --> 35:12.458
The folks who gave me a chance
to redeem myself

35:12.501 --> 35:14.938
after I tried
to destroy the world.

35:14.982 --> 35:16.723
<i>♪</i>

35:16.766 --> 35:18.551
- Yeah, there it is.

35:18.594 --> 35:20.379
- Oh, fantastic work again,
my boy.

35:20.422 --> 35:22.163
- I'll keep an eye out.
- Good thing you speak Russian.

35:22.207 --> 35:24.557
- Oh, yes. Well, I picked it up
working in a lab

35:24.600 --> 35:26.994
with some Russian scientists.
Lovely gentlemen, you know.

35:27.037 --> 35:28.996
Though I never thought I'd be
using it for this, mind you.

35:29.039 --> 35:31.259
- Okay, okay. Let's try this.

35:31.303 --> 35:33.218
Okay, go ahead.
- Okay.

35:59.287 --> 36:00.462
- Okay, okay.
Let's get out of here.

36:00.506 --> 36:01.811
- Yes, let's get out of here.

36:09.776 --> 36:14.520
<i>♪</i>

36:16.304 --> 36:18.219
It worked.
Look, everybody's leaving.

36:18.263 --> 36:19.612
- Yeah, but we won't have time
to run back and warn the gang

36:19.655 --> 36:20.961
before that Waverider shows up.

36:21.004 --> 36:22.528
- We will if we drive.

36:22.571 --> 36:24.573
Let's see if I remember
how to drive stick.

36:24.617 --> 36:26.227
- Oh, wow, wow, wow.

36:26.271 --> 36:28.925
Motorcars of the future
are truly fascinating.

36:28.969 --> 36:29.970
Ah. Okay.

36:32.494 --> 36:34.017
<i>♪</i>

36:34.061 --> 36:35.758
- Well, would you look at that?

36:35.802 --> 36:38.108
We took a little break
from leading the team

36:38.152 --> 36:40.067
and everything turned out fine.

36:40.110 --> 36:42.635
- Yeah. Kids are all grown up,
huh?

36:45.551 --> 36:47.335
- Hey, uh, what's up
with those two?

36:48.380 --> 36:49.598
I think they got in a fight

36:49.642 --> 36:51.557
with a gooseberry bush
and lost.

36:51.600 --> 36:54.995
<i>♪</i>

36:55.038 --> 36:57.476
- You don't think that they--

36:58.651 --> 37:00.870
- No.
- No.

37:03.003 --> 37:04.570
- Any sign of them yet?

37:04.613 --> 37:06.180
- No.

37:06.224 --> 37:08.269
- I hope they didn't
run into any dinosaurs.

37:09.879 --> 37:13.143
- Hey, guys, listen.

37:13.187 --> 37:14.841
- Yeah, what's that weird
noise?

37:14.884 --> 37:16.538
- According to my
audio analysis,

37:16.582 --> 37:18.410
it's a straight-four engine
with manual transmission.

37:18.453 --> 37:19.976
and the squeaking noise
suggests

37:20.020 --> 37:21.630
there's a problem
with the clutch.

37:26.200 --> 37:29.812
<i>♪</i>

37:29.856 --> 37:32.772
- Oh, guess we're not gonna
see those dinosaurs.

37:34.339 --> 37:36.732
- Hey, gang. We need to
get the hell out of here.

37:36.776 --> 37:38.995
- We're in 1986,
just outside of Chernobyl.

37:39.039 --> 37:40.780
What?

37:40.823 --> 37:42.434
- The meltdown's gonna happen
in about 20 minutes.

37:42.477 --> 37:44.131
We did make a small change
to the timeline.

37:44.174 --> 37:45.741
- Okay, hold on.
What did you guys do?

37:45.785 --> 37:48.135
- We broadcast a message
from a military base

37:48.178 --> 37:49.963
informing everyone
that the meltdown was imminent,

37:50.006 --> 37:51.617
that they should flee
immediately.

37:51.660 --> 37:53.358
Well, I wasn't in
good conscience gonna leave

37:53.401 --> 37:54.794
without doing something, was I?

37:54.837 --> 37:56.317
- Okay, okay, okay, okay.

37:56.361 --> 37:57.666
While I definitely
understand, you guys,

37:57.710 --> 38:00.016
that's not a small change
to the timeline.

38:00.060 --> 38:02.236
You've potentially affected
thousands of lives.

38:02.280 --> 38:05.283
- Yeah, and you just put
a huge target on our backs.

38:06.675 --> 38:09.678
<i>- We have another disturbance
in the timeline, Captain.</i>

38:09.722 --> 38:11.550
- Where to, Gideon?

38:11.593 --> 38:14.683
<i>- 1986, the city of Chernobyl
in the Soviet Union.</i>

38:14.727 --> 38:16.816
<i>Guess who is causing
the disturbance.</i>

38:16.859 --> 38:18.731
- Doubt that's necessary.

38:18.774 --> 38:20.646
<i>- Because the Legends
wreak havoc wherever they go.</i>

38:20.689 --> 38:22.387
<i>And you can finally end it
once and for all</i>

38:22.430 --> 38:24.127
<i>by eliminating them for good.</i>

38:24.171 --> 38:26.304
- Didn't you say rash actions

38:26.347 --> 38:28.262
add more ripples
to the timeline?

38:28.306 --> 38:30.612
<i>- Fortunately, we're at an
opportune moment in history.</i>

38:30.656 --> 38:32.614
<i>Any ripple effect you cause
will be negligible</i>

38:32.658 --> 38:35.313
<i>due to its close proximity
to such a catastrophic event.</i>

38:36.314 --> 38:37.532
<i>Are you ready to save
the timeline</i>

38:37.576 --> 38:39.404
<i>from the Legends, Captain?</i>

38:39.447 --> 38:41.362
<i>♪</i>

38:47.586 --> 38:50.328
<i>♪</i>

38:52.678 --> 38:54.593
- What's that noise?
- It's the Waverider.

38:54.636 --> 38:57.422
- Oh, man, you guys need to go
fix that time machine now.

38:57.465 --> 38:59.380
And we need to put out
this fire.

38:59.424 --> 39:02.078
- Be ready. We have no idea
who or what is on that ship.

39:03.123 --> 39:05.778
- Now, if we can wire the
magnetic components together--

39:05.821 --> 39:08.911
- We can bridge the electric
current from the compass

39:08.955 --> 39:11.871
to the ignition coil
and start the machine.

39:11.914 --> 39:14.221
- Absolutely fantastic work,
young lady.

39:14.264 --> 39:15.918
Fantastic. Very well.

39:15.962 --> 39:18.530
- Hey, Zari? I've been doing
a lot of thinking.

39:19.705 --> 39:21.663
- Y-y-you want to talk
right now?

39:21.707 --> 39:23.186
- If I don't get this
off my chest,

39:23.230 --> 39:25.406
I won't be able to think
about anything else.

39:25.450 --> 39:27.016
- Go for it. I got it.

39:30.585 --> 39:33.849
- Yes, I want to live
in the totem with you.

39:33.893 --> 39:36.765
- You do?
Are you--are you--are you sure?

39:36.809 --> 39:38.463
You haven't had a lot of time
to think about it.

39:38.506 --> 39:40.900
- You don't get it.
It doesn't matter where I go,

39:40.943 --> 39:43.293
as long as I'm with you.

39:43.337 --> 39:46.906
<i>♪</i>

39:46.949 --> 39:49.082
- Ah, yes, we need more wire.

39:49.125 --> 39:50.953
- Mm. I got it.

39:50.997 --> 39:52.520
This is very us.
- This is so us.

39:52.564 --> 39:54.957
- Yeah.

40:00.441 --> 40:01.790
- Here it comes.

40:01.834 --> 40:03.270
- Not if I stop it first.

40:03.313 --> 40:05.054
- No, come on, we gotta go.
Let's go.

40:05.098 --> 40:08.493
<i>♪</i>

40:08.536 --> 40:10.408
<i>- We're right above
the Legends, Captain.</i>

40:10.451 --> 40:12.453
<i>Only you can engage
our weapons.</i>

40:12.497 --> 40:14.934
<i>It's time to prove to me that
you're the man I know you are.</i>

40:14.977 --> 40:19.199
<i>♪</i>

40:19.242 --> 40:21.419
- Oh, I'm sorry, Gideon,
I just can't do it.

40:21.462 --> 40:24.291
I just can't kill the Legends.

40:24.334 --> 40:27.555
Sure, they used me,
but they used me to do good.

40:27.599 --> 40:28.904
<i>- Please return to your seat
and focus</i>

40:28.948 --> 40:30.558
<i>on the mission, Captain.</i>

40:30.602 --> 40:32.473
- Also one of these days,
you're just gonna shoot me

40:32.517 --> 40:34.388
out of the cargo bay like you
did with Time Mistress Ava.

40:34.432 --> 40:36.521
And I'd rather die
with a little more dignity!

40:36.564 --> 40:37.826
<i>- There's nowhere to run.</i>

40:37.870 --> 40:39.741
- Wrong about that, Gideon.

40:39.785 --> 40:41.961
<i>- No.
Do not go into section A2.</i>

40:45.399 --> 40:47.793
<i>♪</i>

40:53.755 --> 40:56.758
That thing I just said
about dying with dignity?

40:56.802 --> 40:58.194
I lied.

40:58.238 --> 40:59.761
<i>♪</i>

40:59.805 --> 41:02.329
Dignity is overrated.

41:06.333 --> 41:11.251
<i>♪</i>

41:11.294 --> 41:12.731
- Yes.

41:15.647 --> 41:18.171
<i>♪</i>

41:21.304 --> 41:23.655
- What is that?

41:23.698 --> 41:25.744
- Whoa,
it's coming straight for us.

41:25.787 --> 41:28.311
- Is that someone on a toilet?
- Who cares? Let's go.

41:31.314 --> 41:32.968
- Somebody press
the red button.

41:33.012 --> 41:34.840
- Whoever it is, they're gonna
land right on top of us.

41:34.883 --> 41:36.363
<i>♪</i>

41:38.060 --> 41:41.542
<i>♪</i>

41:43.544 --> 41:45.372
Oh, crap!

41:53.815 --> 42:00.866
<i>♪</i>

42:10.005 --> 42:11.529
- Greg, move your head.
